<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-268-483  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 268 483.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommuting Review: the Gordon Report  Jan 1 1989 v6 n1 p1(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Church gains access to 5500 telecommuters after designing owntelephone network.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sandilands, Phillip.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Worldwide Church of God has solved its own uniquetelecommunications problem by designing a system called SWIFT(Supervised WATS In-home Forwarding Technology).andP;  ThePasadena-based church receives over 30,000 calls a week inresponse to its television program 'The World Tomorrow.' Theexisting telephone answering staff could not handle the volume anda call-forwarding system to other areas proved too cumbersome anddifficult to monitor.andP;  Now, 120 of the 249 incoming 800-numberlines are dedicated to SWIFT and those calls can be forwarded tovolunteer phone answerers anywhere in the country.andP;  The more than5,500 volunteers donate about 15 minutes of their time on anygiven weekend.andP;  Anyone with a touchtone phone can participate andall the SWIFT-relayed calls are billed to the church.andP;  Annualsavings are estimated at $500,000._Worldwide Church ofGod_Worldwide Church of GodandM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommunicationsCustomizationCall Routing EquipmentWorldwide Church of GodTelecommutingReligion.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>